      "The book of Acts opens with a goodbye that is really a commissioning. Jesus spends forty days after the resurrection doing what seems like the least dramatic thing possible — eating with his friends and talking about the kingdom. No victory lap. No press tour. Just meals and conversation. And then he says the thing that redefines everything: 'You will be my witnesses in Jerusalem, and in all Judea and Samaria, and to the ends of the earth.'\n\nThe disciples, bless them, are still asking the wrong question: 'Lord, are you going to restore the kingdom to Israel now?' They want a political revolution with a timeline. Jesus gives them a movement with no expiration date. The power they're about to receive isn't for conquest — it's for testimony. And then he's gone. Taken up. A cloud. Two men in white asking the most important question in the New Testament: 'Why do you stand here looking into the sky?'\n\nThat question haunts the rest of the book. The disciples have a choice: keep staring at where Jesus was, or go become what Jesus asked them to be. They choose to move.",
