    summary:
      "This is the story nobody puts on a church welcome banner. Ananias and Sapphira sell a piece of property, keep back part of the price, and bring the rest to the apostles — presenting it as the full amount. Peter confronts Ananias: 'You have not lied to us but to God.' Ananias falls down dead. Three hours later, Sapphira arrives, repeats the lie, and meets the same fate. Young men carry out two bodies. Great fear seizes the whole church.\n\nThe story is shocking because it seems disproportionate. People lie all the time. People exaggerate their generosity constantly. Why the death penalty for a financial fib? But the text is careful to clarify: the sin wasn't keeping the money. Peter explicitly says the property was theirs to keep and the proceeds were theirs to use however they wanted. The sin was pretending to be more generous than they were. It was the performance of devotion without the reality.\n\nThis is the first internal crisis of the church, and it comes not from persecution or theological error but from plain old hypocrisy. The community that was defined by radical honesty encounters its first fake, and the response is terrifying.",
    significance:
      "Ananias and Sapphira is the church's version of the Achan story in Joshua — the first sin after a new beginning that threatens to corrupt the entire community. Just as Achan's hidden plunder endangered Israel after Jericho, the hidden lie endangers the church after Pentecost. Luke is establishing a principle: the Spirit-filled community requires truth as its oxygen. Contaminate the honesty, and you choke the life.\n\nThe severity of the judgment also reveals something about the stakes. In the early church's economy of radical sharing, trust was the currency. If people could lie about their contributions without consequence, the entire system would collapse. The death of Ananias and Sapphira isn't primarily about punishment; it's about the preservation of a community that runs on trust.",
