      "The theological heart of this story is Peter's statement: 'You have not lied to men but to God.' The Holy Spirit isn't an abstract force in Acts; the Spirit is a person who can be lied to, grieved, and tested. This narrative establishes the Spirit's role as the active presence within the community — not merely inspiration for preaching but the one to whom the community is accountable. Lying to the church is lying to the Spirit, because the church is the Spirit's dwelling place. That identification — church as Spirit's temple — will become a major Pauline theme, but Luke establishes it here first through narrative rather than theology.",
    climateNote:
      "Patronage was the dominant economic system in the Greco-Roman world. Wealthy benefactors gave publicly to gain honor and social capital. The temptation Ananias and Sapphira faced was deeply culturally embedded: to receive the social status of total generosity without the actual cost. In a honor-shame culture, the appearance of virtue was often more valuable than the virtue itself. The early church was attempting something countercultural — a community where the truth of your gift mattered more than the impression it made.",
