    summary:
      "Stephen is the first Christian to die for the faith, and he dies giving a history lecture. That's not an exaggeration — his speech before the Sanhedrin is the longest speech in Acts, a sweeping retelling of Israel's story from Abraham to Solomon, and its thesis is devastating: you have always resisted the Holy Spirit. Every prophet you stoned. Every messenger you rejected. And now you've killed the Righteous One himself.\n\nThe speech is brilliant because Stephen doesn't introduce foreign ideas. He uses their own scriptures, their own heroes, their own history, and turns it all into an indictment. Abraham was called to leave. Joseph was rejected by his brothers and exalted in exile. Moses was pushed away by his people and became their deliverer anyway. The pattern is unmistakable: God's chosen instruments are always resisted by God's own people first.\n\nThe stoning is almost cinematic. Stephen looks up and sees heaven opened, Jesus standing at the right hand of God. He kneels, echoing Jesus himself: 'Lord, do not hold this sin against them.' And then, almost as a footnote, Luke mentions a young man named Saul, watching the coats. The future apostle to the Gentiles is introduced at the death of the church's first martyr. Luke's storytelling is surgical.",
