      "Stephen's martyrdom is the event that scatters the church beyond Jerusalem and paradoxically accelerates the very mission Jesus outlined in Acts 1. Persecution becomes the mechanism of expansion. The blood of the martyrs becomes the seed of the church — a pattern that will repeat for three centuries.\n\nStephen's speech also represents the first major theological break. His argument that God doesn't dwell in temples made with hands strikes at the heart of Jewish identity. The temple was the center of everything — religion, economy, national identity. Stephen says it was always too small for God. This idea will become foundational for Paul's theology of the church as the new temple, the body of Christ as the dwelling place of the Spirit.",
    relationalNote:
      "The detail that haunts this passage is the coats. The witnesses laid their garments at the feet of a young man named Saul. He's not throwing stones, but he's holding the jackets of those who are. Complicity doesn't require active participation — sometimes it just looks like making things easier for the people doing the violence. Saul will spend the rest of his life reckoning with this moment. And Stephen's prayer — 'do not hold this sin against them' — may be the prayer that made Paul possible. Forgiveness spoken over your persecutor might be the most powerful evangelistic act in Scripture.",
    conceptualNote:
      "Stephen's retelling of Israel's history introduces a hermeneutical key that runs through the rest of the New Testament: the pattern of rejection and vindication. Joseph, rejected and vindicated. Moses, rejected and vindicated. Jesus, rejected and vindicated. The pattern suggests that divine purposes advance precisely through the resistance they encounter. Opposition doesn't mean you're wrong. Sometimes it means you're exactly right, and the truth is too uncomfortable for the system to absorb. That's a dangerous idea — it can be abused — but in Stephen's mouth, it's backed by centuries of evidence.",
    climateNote:
      "The Sanhedrin was the supreme Jewish council, and by the first century it operated under Roman authority with limited judicial power. Whether they had the legal right to execute Stephen is debated — the stoning may have been a mob action rather than a formal sentence. Either way, the charge against Stephen — speaking against 'this holy place and the law' — reflects the two pillars of Jewish identity under occupation: temple and Torah. To challenge either was to threaten the community's survival. Stephen wasn't killed for blasphemy in the abstract. He was killed because his theology threatened the only institutions holding the nation together.",
